article.headline: Storm weather Holdsclaw's 32-point return
article.linkText: Holdsclaw returns with 32 in loss to Storm
article.story:
WASHINGTON -- Chamique Holdsclaw returned to the Washington
Mystics' lineup, only to be upstaged by the Seattle Storm's one-two
punch.

	   Lauren Jackson had 25 points and 11 rebounds and Sue Bird added
21 as Seattle overcame Holdsclaw's career-high 32 points in an
80-71 victory over the Mystics on Saturday night.

	   Bird and Jackson combined to score 22 of the Storm's final 25
points, helping Seattle overcome a 2-for-13 start from the field in
the first half and a 1-for-8 skid to begin the second.

	   "Lauren and I play well together. We're starting to develop
chemistry,'' Bird said. "I think we complement each other. When we
run the pick-and-roll, we're hard to stop.''

	   Holdsclaw, who also had 11 rebounds, rejoined the Mystics after
missing nine games with a high left ankle sprain sustained June 28.
Washington, which has lost three straight and four of five, was 5-4
in her absence.

	   "It's OK. It's 99.5 percent,'' Holdsclaw said of her ankle. "I
can't cut like I'd like, but I can go out there and still play.
Hopefully ice and a couple of days off will take care of it.''

	   Seattle trailed 66-59 when Bird hit a 3-pointer with 4:45 left
in the game, starting a 12-0 run.

	   Jackson tied the game with 4:04 remaining, converting a short
jumper from the right side after Bird's miss and Bird gave the
Storm the lead for good on a 3-pointer from the top of the key with
3:18 left.

	   "They might have relaxed for a split second when they had the
lead,'' Seattle coach Lin Dunn said. "And we took advantage of
it.''

	   The Storm beat Washington for the first time in four meetings.

	   The Mystics exploited Seattle's 2-for-13 start from the field,
scoring 11 unanswered points for a 13-2 lead with 14:03 left in the
first half.

	   Holdsclaw, who had a hand in Washington's first six points,
showed no rust. She scored the Mystics' first points on a 12-foot
baseline jumper, then sprung Stacey Dales-Schuman on a transition
basket before hitting a pair of free throws.

	   Jackson, who scored 12 first-half points, helped the Storm chip
away. She capped a 9-2 run with a 3-pointer from the left side,
trimming the deficit to 30-25 with 5:19 left in the half, and her
basket with 18.3 seconds to go got Seattle within 41-39 at
halftime.
